🧠 OS Concept 1: Orphan Process
1️⃣ Simple Idea

Orphan Process =
👉 child process whose parent has terminated

🧠 Real-World Analogy

A child whose parent is gone 👶

👉 Someone else must take care

⚙️ What Happens Internally

When parent dies:

👉 OS assigns child to a special process:

👉 init process (PID = 1)

⚙️ Why This Exists

To ensure:

no process is left unmanaged
system stability
🔗 Connection to Zombie (Day 9)
Zombie	Orphan
child finished	parent finished
parent alive	parent dead
🎯 Placement Question

Q: What is orphan process?

👉 A process whose parent has terminated and is adopted by init process.

🧠 Memory Trick
Orphan = parent gone
🧠 OS Concept 2: System Boot Process
1️⃣ Simple Idea

Booting =
👉 starting the computer and loading OS into memory

🧠 Real-World Analogy

Waking up your brain 🧠

Before working, system must:

initialize
load instructions
⚙️ Steps of Booting
1️⃣ Power ON

Computer starts

2️⃣ BIOS / UEFI

Checks hardware

👉 RAM, keyboard, disk

3️⃣ Bootloader

Loads OS into RAM

4️⃣ OS Starts

Kernel begins execution

🔗 Connection to OS

After boot:

👉 OS takes full control

🎯 Placement Question

Q: What is booting?

👉 Process of loading OS into memory during startup.

🧠 Memory Trick
Boot = Start OS
⚙️ COA Concept 3: Flynn’s Classification

🔥 Important theory question

1️⃣ Simple Idea

Flynn’s classification =
👉 types of computer architecture based on:

instruction streams
data streams
⚙️ Types
1️⃣ SISD (Single Instruction Single Data)

👉 normal computer

1 instruction → 1 data
2️⃣ SIMD

👉 same instruction, multiple data

Example:

image processing
GPUs
3️⃣ MISD (rare)

👉 multiple instruction, single data

(Not common)

4️⃣ MIMD 🔥

👉 multiple instruction, multiple data

Example:

multi-core CPU
🧠 Real-World Analogy
SIMD

Teacher gives same problem to whole class

MIMD

Each student solves different problems

🎯 Placement Question

Q: What is MIMD?

👉 Multiple instructions executed on multiple data simultaneously.

🧠 Memory Trick
SI = Single Instruction
MI = Multiple Instruction
SD = Single Data
MD = Multiple Data
⚙️ COA Concept 4: Parallel Processing
1️⃣ Simple Idea

Parallel Processing =
👉 doing multiple tasks at same time

🧠 Real-World Analogy

Cooking multiple dishes 🍳

Instead of:

making one dish fully
then next

You cook all simultaneously

⚙️ Types
1️⃣ Bit-level

process multiple bits

2️⃣ Instruction-level

multiple instructions (pipelining)

3️⃣ Task-level

multiple tasks

🔗 Connection to Multi-Core CPU

Modern CPUs:

👉 use parallel processing

🎯 Placement Question

Q: What is parallel processing?

👉 Executing multiple computations simultaneously.

🧠 Memory Trick
Parallel = Same time execution
